all the assets that

00:46:40.690 --> 00:46:42.700
are being used in this
portion of the game

00:46:42.700 --> 00:46:47.650
are tagged and time-stamped, the
portions of code that are used.

00:46:47.650 --> 00:46:50.020
And once this recording
experience is over

00:46:50.020 --> 00:46:52.510
and you finish killing
all these zombies,

00:46:52.510 --> 00:46:55.330
you then can go into
the refactor stage.

00:46:55.330 --> 00:46:58.210
And the refactor stage will look
a little bit familiar to you

00:46:58.210 --> 00:47:02.230
probably if you're familiar
with nonlinear editing suites.

00:47:02.230 --> 00:47:05.890
So what's happened is there's
been a screen capture created

00:47:05.890 --> 00:47:08.480
while you've been recording
what assets are used.

00:47:08.480 --> 00:47:10.060
So you can understand
exactly where

00:47:10.060 --> 00:47:12.880
you are when you're
trying to understand

00:47:12.880 --> 00:47:14.770
where this asset was used.

00:47:14.770 --> 00:47:17.470
And all of the assets
are clustered together.

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:19.780
You can drill down
into each one of them,

00:47:19.780 --> 00:47:21.930
and you can swap out
assets and hide them.

00:47:24.700 --> 00:47:26.680
And that red bar
there determines

00:47:26.680 --> 00:47:29.410
where the APK cutoff will be.

00:47:29.410 --> 00:47:33.610
So you move it to the left, all
the numbers of files go down

00:47:33.610 --> 00:47:35.100
as well as the megabytes.

00:47:35.100 --> 00:47:37.480
And conversely, as you
move it to the right,

00:47:37.480 --> 00:47:39.040
you're getting a bigger game.

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:42.850
But this allows you
with pinpoint accuracy

00:47:42.850 --> 00:47:45.100
to figure out what
portions of your game

00:47:45.100 --> 00:47:49.000
make a great fit for
instant and greatly reduces

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:54.685
the skill involved that would
otherwise require refactoring.

00:47:54.685 --> 00:47:57.700
And so now you're just going
back into the regular flow--

